<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-61-1245 </DOCNO><TEXT>Renewable sources of energy must appear as good investments and must matchbetter established technology in terms of delivered energy, reliabilityand convenience if they are to gain entry into the commercial market.The degree of success in providing hard evidence of these features throughdemonstration schemes is examined. Although results from demonstrationprogrammes are encouraging it has been difficult to obtain and maintaincommitment to demonstration projects because the inherent risks are stilltoo high for entrepreneurs. Substantial government or other public fundswill be required for a limited transition period to support demonstrations,disseminate the results and encourage replication in the market. Thereis an urgent need for effective presentation of the evidence of potentialmarket viability to stimulate market take-up. The interest and imaginationof the public has been captured by renewable energy technology creatinga positive climate for the development of a market. The critical issueis how this potential can be realized in terms of a self-sustaining businesssector. (U.K.).</TEXT></DOC>